elp farms with interest, feed or water</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-02-06T05:34:11.596Z","body":"<p>Tony Abbott has flagged plans to bring forward a new farm household allowance to assist drought-affected farmers with dole-equivalent income support, but the government has yet to finalise a substantial package to help farm businesses with interest, feed or water.<br></p><p><a href=\"http://www.daff.gov.au/about/budget/budget-2013-14/national-drought-program-reform-q-and-a\">The $99.4m package</a>, which was outlined by the former Labor government and due to start in July, includes the farm household allowance to put food on the table – equivalent to the Newstart rate – paid to eligible farmers for up to three years.<br></p><p>The allowance payment is a rebadging of the <a href=\"http://www.daff.gov.au/agriculture-food/drought/assistance/tffp/faq\">transitional farm family payment</a>.<br></p><p>“The commonwealth and the states agreed they would move from on an old system to a new system, a system that involves providing income support to people who are in exceptional circumstances drought,” the prime minister said.<br></p><p>“What I would like to do is essentially bring forward the start of that scheme and that’s what we are looking at now.”<br></p><p>National party members were discussing drought policy options at their first party room meeting in Bundaberg on Thursday as the party leader, Warren Truss, and the agriculture minister, Barnaby Joyce, prepared a drought package for cabinet next week.<br></p><p>The Nationals are expected to endorse a hybrid plan which would include a form of the interest payment subsidy that was a feature of the Howard government’s exceptional circumstances model. Under that policy, farmers who passed an assets test were paid subsidies of up to $100,000 each year for a maximum five years in drought-declared areas.<br></p><p>Interest payments remain a key plank of National party policy. However, in a week when the treasurer, Joe Hockey, declared the end of the “age of entitlement”, there appears to be little support among Liberal ranks for the payments, even among rural MPs.<br></p><p>Nationals senator John Williams called for a return to interest subsidies to address debt, which he described as the biggest issue for farmers facing drought. He said farmers were worse off due to the actions of the previous government, which temporarily stopped the live animal export trade after allegations of animal cruelty. Williams also blamed Labor for the high dollar.<br></p><p>“We’ve got generations of people on the land with huge experience and know-how,” Williams told the ABC. “They are the best people to run that land and when governments help to bring them down then governments should help to stand them back up.<br></p><p>“We need to support our farmers through three good seasons – average rain, good commodity prices, low interest rates – to let our farmers get back on their feet, then they can cope for themselves.”<br></p><p>But the Labor agriculture spokesman, Joel Fitzgibbon, said bringing forward the farm household allowance would not make a big difference to farmers. He called on the government to reduce the concessional interest rate for drought-affected farms and convene state and territory ministers through the Council of Australian Government process to complete national drought reform.<br></p><p>“While any bring-forward would be welcomed, there is little difference between the post 1 July  regime and the current transitional farm household payment which is in place to bridge the gap between the old Exceptional Circumstances payment and the new 1 July  payment,” Fitzgibbon said.<br></p><p>The NSW Farmers Association president, Fiona Simson, welcomed the move to bring forward the farm household allowance but warned that any long-term drought policy would require a “multifaceted approach” with major government investment in the agricultural industry and rural communities.<br></p><p>Simson also said the new farm household allowance contained an assets test which ruled out most farm businesses by capping eligibility for assets at $1.5m, including the farm. Assets and viability tests also applied to concessional loans, where farms could swap private debt for a lower rate government loan. It is understood the government is considering a relaxation of the eligibility criteria.<br></p><p>“Any recognition now by the government of drought is good but as we’ve said for a long time, drought does not just affect farmers, it affects communities,” Simson said.<br></p><p>She called for a debate on innovative ideas to support agriculture and rural communities.<br></p><p>She raised two schemes to address farms shedding workers during natural disasters such as drought. The first was a regional employment development scheme used in the 1970s to employ people in regional areas to support local infrastructure projects. The second was a drought employment support program where the unemployment payment was paid to the farmer to keep on workers during drought when extra labour was even more crucial.<br></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">“Whilst small Band-aid solutions are good, we also need a full suite of policies. It’s going to take a large investment and it is up to the government what form it takes,” she said.</span><br></p>","headline":"Tony Abbott to bring forward income support for drought-hit farmers","trailText":"Package will put food on the table but government has yet to finalise package to help farms with interest, feed or water","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mgxq","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391664415109/b5b7e8f8-fbbc-43b6-bac8-541b05573cea-140x84.png","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391664415109/b5b7e8f8-fbbc-43b6-bac8-541b05573cea-140x84.p