ng director, Mark Scott, has refused Tony Abbott’s calls for the national broadcaster to apologise for its handling of allegations made by asylum seekers against the Australian navy.<br></p><p>Facing continued fire from the Coalition government and criticism from <a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s3937354.htm\">the ABC’s Media Watch</a>, Scott defended his stance and <a href=\"http://about.abc.net.au/press-releases/abc-statement/\">his recent statement making no apologies but acknowledging the reporting could have been more precise</a>.<br></p><p>“If there is imprecise wording … and anyone interpreted that that the ABC had been judge and jury on this, we certainly don’t want that to be the case,” said Scott.<br></p><p>\"We never sought to be judge and jury on this matter. We do not know what went on on that boat.”<br></p><p>Scott said throughout the ABC’s history, there had been stories that “people disagree with” but that it was “par for the course” for media organisations and insisted he was “standing firm” in his role.<br></p><p>“There is some suggestion here that those allegations shouldn’t have been reported. There’s some suggestion here that that video tape should not have been aired,” Scott said.<br></p><p>“We stand by the thrust of the story and I think it’s important that we be judged on that story,” he said.<br></p><p>\"We know that the coverage of<a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23asylumseekers&amp;src=hash\"> </a>asylum seekers has been contentious.\"<br></p><p>Abbott and his <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/feb/05/abc-should-have-been-more-sceptical-malcolm-turnbull\">communications minister, Malcolm Turnbull</a>, with responsibility for the ABC, have been critical of the ABC’s coverage of a story that detailed allegations that asylum seekers had suffered burns when navy personnel made them hold on to hot engine pipes as boats were turned back to Indonesia.<br></p><p>Scott made reference to criticism of the ABC by a number of columnists who were “leading the charge” against the national broadcaster and suggested \"some of that is ideological and some of it is commercial”.<br></p><p>The government is <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/05/australia-network-overtaken-by-technology-malcolm-turnbull\">reviewing the 10-year $223m Australia Network contract</a>, which was awarded to the ABC by the former Labor government after intense and controversial competition with Sky News. The auditor general subsequently criticised the tender process.<br></p><p>Scott said there would always be critics but it was his belief, backed by all of the research seen by the ABC, that the broadcaster operated \"with the strong support of the Australian people\".<br></p><p>Scott took talkback calls after his interview with the ABC's Jon Faine, with some callers highly supportive of the broadcaster, some critical and one angry that the ABC's reporting did not demonstrate \"a love of Australia\".<br></p><p><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">On Wednesday, </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/05/tony-abbott-sorry-seems-to-be-the-hardest-word-for-the-abc\" style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">the prime minister suggested that “sorry seems to be the hardest word”</a><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\"> for the ABC and expressed his disappointment at the coverage of the navy.</span><br></p>","headline":"ABC chief Mark Scott refuses Tony Abbott's call for apology to navy","trailText":"Broadcaster defends its handling of burns allegations by asylum seekers, saying 'we never sought to be judge and jury'","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mgxv","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391651812048/98253aa4-55d5-486b-a25c-fd51c1f2d887-140x84.jpeg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391651812048/98253aa4