https://www.coagreformcouncil.gov.au/\">Council of Australian Governments (Coag) reform council</a> released its final review of the performance of governments in achieving reforms across 45 areas. The reform council found that 31 of the 45 areas had achieved significant reforms.</p><p>Among the key achievements listed by the council were a national health practitioner registration and accreditation system, ensuring nationally consistent standards for a range of health professionals, and an Australian consumer law providing a single national set of consumer protections.</p><p>However, it concluded that “some important reforms remain to be done and need further attention from Coag”. Among the 11 areas which have achieved only partial completion are occupational health and safety regulation and a framework for governments to act to ensure the adequacy of energy market investment.</p><p>On occupational health and safety, the council noted that the reform measures which were designed to create nationally uniform OHS laws to reduce compliance costs for business and promote safer, healthier workplaces, have failed to have been addressed. It noted that Victoria and Western Australia have not enacted laws, while NSW, Queensland, South Australia and the ACT have laws which differ from the model national law.</p><p>Similarly, the council found that there is no nationally consistent mine safety regime as no government had enacted the national core mine safety laws and regulations.  </p><p>While some reforms were found to be partially completed, three reforms dealing with energy pricing and road regulation were designated to be “off track”. The aim of removing energy retail pricing, according to the council, is to allow retailers to set prices that reflect the true cost of energy supply. The council asserted this “sends signals to consumers to manage their energy consumption (otherwise known as active demand side participation)”. However, the council noted that over the past five years, only Victoria and South Australia have removed energy retail price regulation.</p><p>It noted that reviews to be conducted by the Australian Energy Market Commission were well behind schedule. The review of prices in NSW was only completed in 2013 – a year behind schedule – and the review of Queensland prices, which was due to be completed in 2013, has yet to be started. The Queensland state government has, however, pledged to remove electricity price regulation in southeast Queensland by 1 July, 2015.</p><p>The lack of progress on energy reform also fed into the council’s finding that progress on measures to establish “a simpler and consistent national approach to economic regulation of significant infrastructure” has only been partially completed. This reform is intended to ensure the consistent regulation of access to nationally significant infrastructure services, such as the electricity grid, rail networks and port facilities. It aims to “reduce the regulatory uncertainty and compliance costs” for owners, users and investors of nationally significant infrastructure.</p><p>The council found that while most state and federal infrastructure areas were compliant with the reforms, it noted the reform in all energy access regimes in national energy market jurisdictions, the Victorian rail access regime and the Western Australian gas access regime remained to be completed.</p><p>The council’s report also confirmed the findings of its “Lessons for Federal Reform” report, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/06/coag-reform-activity-has-slowed-says-new-report\">released last November</a>, that progress on reform is significantly enhanced through reward payments. The council noted that “governments have made better progress implementing the reforms that attract reward payments than they have made on the reforms that do not attract reward payments”. It found that governments have completed 21 of 26 reforms in which rewards were offered and only 10 of 19 reforms where no reward was offered.</p><p>The chairman of the reform council, former Victorian premier John Brumby, in his letter to the prime minister, Tony Abbott presenting the report, recommended that in considering any future reforms, Coag should “take note that greater progress was made on reforms that attracted reward payments under this agreement than on those reforms that did not attract reward payments”.</p>","headline":"Coag reform review: still a way to go for a ‘seamless national economy’","trailText":"Review identifies significant reforms in 31 out of 45 areas, but a lack of progress on energy reform ","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mfxy","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/5/1391565681659/9c37185c-8675-4bec-8b26-923b84e45313-140x84.jpeg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/5/1391565681659/9c37185c-8675-4bec-8b26-923b84e45313-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"720","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"428934968","allowUgc":"false","internalComposerCode":"52f19933e4b025fe0e2e663e","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Greg Jericho","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-05T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2038332","productionOffice":"AUS","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-08T20:15:16Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/news/2014/feb/06/coag-reform-review-still-a-way-to-go-for-a-seamless-national-economy","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/news/2014/feb/06/coag-reform-review-still-a-way-to-go-for-a-seamless-national-economy","tags":[{"id":"global/council-of-australian-governments","webTitle":"Council of Australian Governments","type":"keyword","sectionId":"news","sectionName":"News","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/global/council-of-australian-governments","apiUrl":"http://