onDate":"2014-02-05T21:26:13Z","sectionName":"World news","sectionId":"world","id":"world/2014/feb/06/schapelle-corby-parole-final-decision-imminent","fields":{"standfirst":"<p>Indonesia's justice minister says: 'I will finalise all on Friday. All will be processed equally – no special treatment whatsoever'</p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-02-05T21:26:12.642Z","body":"<p>Indonesian authorities have confirmed a final decision on Schapelle Corby's parole bid is imminent, with a decision on her release to be finalised on Friday.<br></p><p>Corby has spent almost nine years in Kerobokan jail in Indonesia after being convicted of trying to smuggle 4.2kg of marijuana into Bali in 2004.</p><p>Indonesia's justice minister, Amir Syamsuddin, said: \"I will finalise all on Friday. All will be processed equally – no special treatment whatsoever.\"</p><p>The parole application is one of 1700 applications for parole before the minister. It is believed to have good prospects of success and Syamsuddin said he could see no reason why Corby's bid would be rejected.</p><p>Last year Indonesian authorities issued Corby a passport, which is believed to be a positive sign. Corby had a closed-door parole hearing in Bali last week.</p><p>Australia’s prime minister, Tony Abbott, has avoided commenting on Corby's case, saying it was a matter for Indonesia.</p><p>“This is ultimately a matter for the Indonesian justice system, obviously the Indonesian justice system is a little different to ours but it’s theirs and Australians who go to Indonesia are inevitably going to be subject to their justice system, just as Indonesians who come to Australia are subject to our justice system,” he said.</p><p>“Generally speaking, the less said about consular cases the better, so let’s see what the system produces.”</p><p>Corby will serve her parole in the Kuta district in Bali if it is approved, where her sister Mercedes has a home.</p>","headline":"Schapelle Corby's parole: final decision